BSE - Czech Republic 20010609.1127
BSE - Czech Republic: OIE confirmed 20010616.1160
Date: 31 Aug 2001
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: OIE Paris, Vol. 14 - No. 35 [edited
<http://www.oie.int/eng/info/hebdo/a_current.htm#Sec0>

[A second case of BSE has been reported in the republic as a result of
their surveillance. - Mod.MHJ
Bovine spongiform encephalopathy in the Czech Republic
---------------------------------------------------------
Emergency report
See also: 3 Aug 2001, 15 Jun 2001
Information received on 24 August 2001 from Dr Josef Holejsovsky, Chief
Veterinary Officer, State Veterinary Administration, Prague:
Report date: 24 Aug 2001
Nature of diagnosis: laboratory
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 21 Aug 2001
Outbreaks:
Location: Zdar nad Sazavou
No. of outbreaks: 1
Description of affected population: the affected animal was a 72-month-old
cow from a holding of breeding cows. Before being slaughtered on 20 Aug
2001 it had not moved from the farm where it was born on 16 Aug 1995.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
species: bov
susceptible: 6
cases: 1
deaths: 0
destroyed: 6
slaughtered: 0
Diagnosis: the animal was tested within the framework of the compulsory
testing for BSE of all bovine animals over 30 months of age subject to
slaughter.
A. Laboratory where diagnosis was made: State Veterinary Institute,
Jihlava. Confirmation at the State Veterinary Institute, Prague (National
Reference Laboratory for transmissible spongiform encephalopathies).
B. Diagnostic tests used: Western blot, immunohistochemistry.
Source of agent / origin of infection: not yet known. Investigations are in
progress.
Control measures: in the herd of origin: eradication by the methods "cohort
cull" and offspring cull. Animals found to be positive will be destroyed by
incineration. In the case of negative test results, the animals will be
destroyed by rendering.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The 3 Aug 2001 report had stated: "Information received on 25 July 2001
from Dr Josef Holejsovsky, Chief Veterinary Officer, State Veterinary
Administration, Prague: Report date: 16 July 2001. Since 12 Jun 2001, all
cattle over 30 months of age subject to slaughter are compulsorily tested
for bovine spongiform encephalopathy (BSE). From 10 July 2001, these tests
were extended to include emergency slaughtered cattle over 24 months of
age. Up to 16 July, a total of 23 054 tests were performed. With the
exception of the case detected on 5 June in Jihlava district (see Disease
Information, 14 [24, 143, dated 15 June 2001), all tests were negative." -
Mod.MHJ
